Lagos State Governor Babajide Sanwo-Olu has broken the ground for the commencement of the construction of Oak Heights, the first of its kind in Eko Atlantic City. The Oak Heights is projected as a residential high-rise of 33 floors in the Eko Atlantic City, built as the solution to the challenges of the overflow of the Atlantic Ocean to shores of Victoria Island in Lagos more than a decade ago.   Lagos records 276 building collapse     Russia-Ukraine conflict: ‘West Africa at risk of food…     Plateau unveils energy efficiency code to curb erratic power   The Chief Executive Officer (CEO),The Oak Holdings, Mr. Olukayode Olusanya, said the Oak Heights is designed to be the tallest residential building dotting the skylines of Eko Atlantic City. He said the development “echoes architectural magnificence in luxury buildings and finesse in real estate engineering”. Olusanya added: “The apartments boast of the opulence of fine spacious living where residents can enjoy about 50,000 square metres of expansive building area, 75-foot long pool, spa rooms with an ambience of ease, top of the line fitness centres, tranquil and lavishly appointed conference rooms, maisonettes and villas with suspended pools, apartments with generous living spaces and ultra-luxury finishes.” He said the Oak Heights brings to life a new type of structure that embodies the 21st century of technical ingenuity and extreme inequality, adding that the building represents a heady confluence of engineering prowess, architectural phenomenon and an unparalleled concentration of personal wealth.